Preheat your oven to 200°C. Trim the @butternut squash{1} then halve lengthways (no
need to peel) and scoop out the seeds. Chop it widthways into 2cm lengths, then
chop into 2cm chunks. Pop on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{} and season with
half the @Mexican style spice mix{1} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Toss to coat
then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until soft and golden,
turning halfway through cooking, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil over high heat. When boiling, stir
in and dissolve half the @chicken stock powder{1}. Stir in the @quinoa{120%g}
and bring back to the boil. Lower the heat and simmer until the quinoa has
doubled in size and the seed has visibly spit, ~{12-15%minutes}. Drain into a
#sieve{} and return to the pan off the heat. Cover with a #lid{} and set aside.

Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into small pieces.
Zest the @lime{1} then chop into wedges. Drain and rinse the @red kidney beans{1}
in the sieve.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, add the
@diced chicken thigh{260%g} and stir-fry until browned all over, ~{4-5%minutes}.
Lower the heat and stir in the remaining Mexican spice and the peppers. Cook,
stirring, for another ~{2%minutes}. Pour in the @tomato passata{1} and remaining
stock powder, stir in half the kidney beans and bring to the boil. Reduce the
heat and simmer until thick and tomatoey, ~{6-8%minutes}, stirring occasionally.

When the quinoa is cooked and drained add the lime zest and the remaining kidney
beans. Gently stir through. Season to taste with salt and pepper if needed. Stir
the roasted squash and a squeeze of lime juice into your chilli and season to
taste with salt and pepper if needed.

Serve the quinoa in #bowls{} topped with the Mexican Chilli. Finish with any
remaining lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!